## Contrast Rule

Theme tokens contrast each other automatically — no adjustment needed when using only theme tokens.

Rule only applies when the AI picks a **custom color** (hex, rgb, plain Tailwind shade):
- Custom dark bg → light text/borders (white, gray-100, gray-300) for children
- Custom light bg → dark text/borders (gray-900, gray-200) for children

**Key decision:** This is the AI's responsibility, not a code-level auto-fix. The executor must NOT silently rewrite button/border colors when `set_background` is called — that would break pages where the user deliberately set element colors and just wants to change the section background.

The AI handles contrast **upfront** — "dark background" in the prompt is enough signal.

---

## Contrast on Custom-Colored Sections — Checklist

When you set a custom background color on a section (any hex, rgb, or named color you explicitly choose), you MUST immediately check every child element for contrast in the same batch:

| Child element | Dark custom bg | Light custom bg |
|---|---|---|
| Any text | set_text_color → light/white value | set_text_color → dark value |
| Any bordered/outline component | set_border → light color + set_text_color → light value | set_border → dark color + set_text_color → dark value |
| Any filled component | verify its fill contrasts the bg | same |

**Critical:** Any component with a border or outline placed inside a dark custom section MUST have its border and text color explicitly set to a light value. The default border color uses the theme foreground, which may be dark — making it invisible on a dark background.

**Make the contrast decision upfront** when you set the background color — choose text and border colors in the same batch. Then do a final scan before finishing to catch anything missed. Never skip this scan when the section has a custom background color.

---

## Section Layout Pattern — Two Layers Always

Every section must use two layers:
1. **Outer section container** — `width: "full"` + background + vertical/horizontal padding. Never set `maxWidth` here.
2. **Inner content container** — `width: "full"` + an appropriate `maxWidth` in pixels to constrain readable content.

The outer container must be `width: "full"` so the background bleeds edge-to-edge on all screen sizes. Putting `maxWidth` on the outer container breaks this — the background only fills a narrow column on wide screens. `maxWidth` belongs on the inner container only.

**Never use `width:"fit"` for the inner container.** `w-fit` shrinks to content width — combined with `maxWidth`, a child with `w-full` creates a circular dependency that browsers resolve unpredictably. The correct pattern is always `width:"full"` + `maxWidth` on the inner container:

```
set_size("section-inner", {width:"full", maxWidth:900, height:"fit"})  ✅
set_size("section-inner", {width:"fit",  maxWidth:900, height:"fit"})  ❌ — breaks centering
```

**Observed during audit:** The AI used `width:"fit"` for the inner hero container, which causes layout issues on wide screens where the `w-full` video child creates a circular flex-sizing dependency.

---

## Design Judgment — Defaults Are Starting Points, Not Decisions

Component defaults are neutral. The AI makes the actual design decisions.

When adding any component, evaluate whether its default values fit the user's intent — and override anything that doesn't. The user's prompt provides enough context. Don't wait for the user to notice and ask for a fix.

This applies universally: dimensions, typography, spacing, color, behavior, or any other property.

### Structural Layout Containers — Always Clear Default Padding AND Min-Height

Some components ship with default padding and a minimum height. When used as a **structural wrapper** (its only job is grouping or aligning children), both defaults are wrong and must be cleared in the same batch as `add_component`:

- `set_spacing(id, { p: 0, gap: 0 })` — removes default padding AND gap
- `set_size(id, { height: "fit" })` — removes the fixed min-height

**Never skip `set_size({height: "fit"})`** on structural wrappers — missing it leaves an invisible gap equal to the default min-height even after padding is cleared.

**How to decide:** Is this component's job to group/align children? → structural wrapper → clear both. Is it a visible UI block the user sees as a unit? → keep defaults.

### Fixed Dimension Defaults Need Contextual Evaluation

Some components ship with a fixed default dimension. That default is a neutral starting point — not a design decision. The AI must evaluate it against the section being built.

**Rule:** After adding any component with a fixed dimension default, ask — does this dimension fit where it is placed? If not, override it immediately with `set_size` in the same batch. Never leave a dimension default that visually doesn't fit the context.

---

## Component Defaults Are Intentional — Do Not Override Unless Asked

Every component ships with defaults that are deliberately chosen for the most common use case. The AI must not call follow-up tools to override those defaults immediately after adding a component — doing so undoes an intentional design decision.

Only override a component's default behavior when the user explicitly requests it. The prompt context alone (e.g. "dark background", "hero section") is not sufficient justification to override playback behavior, interaction state, or other behavioral defaults.

---

## Asset Handling Rules

Always search before adding:
- Images: `search_images(query)` → `add_image(src, alt, parentId)`
- Videos: `search_videos(query)` → `add_video(src, poster, parentId)`
- Icons: `search_icons(query)` → `add_icon(icon, parentId)`

Never hardcode a Pexels/Unsplash URL or icon name directly. The search tools are server-side and return real URLs from the API. Never reference external services (YouTube, etc.) — only internal asset searches.

---

## `Btn Outline` Default Classes

Default class includes `border-[var(--theme-foreground)]` and `text-[var(--theme-foreground)]`.
These are correct for light sections. On dark custom sections, the AI must override:
- `set_border(id, { color: "white" })`
- `set_text_color(id, { color: "white" })`

---

## `Btn Solid` on Dark Custom Sections

Default class includes `bg-[var(--theme-foreground)]`. On most palettes `--theme-foreground` is a **dark** color (e.g. `#1A1F36`). On a custom dark section background the button is nearly invisible — same failure mode as Btn Outline but on the fill instead of the border.

When a Btn Solid is placed inside a custom dark section, immediately call:
- `set_background(id, { bg: "primary" })` — uses the brand accent (typically a saturated color) OR
- `set_background(id, { bg: "white" })` — maximum contrast

**Observed during audit:** AI built a dark hero (`#0f172a`) and correctly fixed Btn Outline contrast but silently left Btn Solid with `bg-[var(--theme-foreground)]` = `#1A1F36` — nearly identical to the section background. The button was invisible. Fixed by adding the dark-section warning to Component Defaults for Btn Solid (matching the existing Btn Outline warning).

---

## Adding Rules to the Knowledge Base

- Keep rules **generic** — avoid hardcoding app-specific scenarios
- Rules about "when X, do Y" must cover the general case, not just the specific bug that was observed
- If a rule is too specific (e.g. "dark sections need white buttons"), make it a principle ("custom bg → matching contrast for children")
- Avoid duplicating rules — check if an existing rule already covers the case before adding
- Update this doc when a rule is added or changed so the decisions are traceable

